            {
               "id": "biodef",
               "text": "<p><h3>Biological group</h3>The classification of living beings began centuries ago with Carl Linnaeus (<htcite0>), and has since undergone continuous refinement, culminating in the taxonomy method consisting of five steps (<htcite1>): <ol> <li>Acquisition of species.</li> <li>Comparison of species with known groups of living beings.</li> <li>Verification of whether the species has already been described; if not, a complete description is created and a name is assigned according to international standards.</li> <li>Determination of the species' classification based on existing classifications.</li> <li>Suggestion of the evolutionary scenario for the species.</li></ol></p><p>Throughout the classification process, species are organized into \"ranks\"  following a hierarchy, ranging from the most inclusive group (<b>Domain</b>) to the least inclusive (<b>Specie</b>). <b>Table 1</b> provides an illustration of our species' organization according to mandatory biological groups (<htcite2>).</p><p><table class=\"taxonomy\"> <tr><th>Taxonomy group</th><th>Specie groups</th><th>Short explanation</th></tr> <tr><td>Domain</td><td>Eukaryota</td><td>Organisms composed of one or multiple cells possess a well-defined nucleus where their DNA is housed (<htcite3>).</td></tr> <tr><td>Kingdom</td><td>Animalia</td><td>Multicellular organisms exhibit muscles and mobility (<htcite4>).</td></tr> <tr><td>Phylum</td><td>Chordates</td><td>Animals that develop a notochord, a dorsal support structure at some stage of their life (<htcite5>).</td></tr> <tr><td>Class</td><td>Mammalia</td><td>Vertebrate animals with mammary glands for nursing their offspring, possessing fur, a diaphragm, and a unique skeletal organization (<htcite6>).</td></tr>  <tr><td>Order</td><td>Primates</td><td>Animals with a large skull, forward-facing eyes, and five fingers on each limb (<htcite7>).</td></tr> <tr><td>Family</td><td>Hominidae</td><td>A group that includes large primates, including humans, due to shared genetic characteristics (<htcite8>).</td></tr> <tr><td>Specie</td><td>Homo sapiens</td><td>Bipedal organisms with large brains and a more pronounced lower jaw compared to the upper jaw (<htcite9>).</td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Groups in which our species is included according to taxonomy.</p><p>In taxonomy, the definition of family is a broader group that includes not only our species but also other species of the genus <i>Homo</i> (<htcite10>).</p><p class=\"reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Regarding superiority</b><br />The definition of <b>Family</b>  in taxonomy encompasses a larger group compared to families in the studies of Morgan and Engels (<htcite11>). This leads us to the conclusion that everyone belongs to the same species, without differences. Do you find this understanding acceptable?<br />&nbsp;</p>",
